<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-570-102  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 570 102.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  August 28 1989 v6 n34 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lotus software will collect data from Dow Jones.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ferranti, Marc.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    LOTS.andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentBeta TestingDow Jones News-Retrieval (Information retrieval system)Information Utilities.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Marc FerrantiandM;Lotus Development Corp. is on the eve of shipping to beta-test sites aprogram that automates the collection of news and stock quotes from Dow JonesNews Retrieval databases, Lotus officials confirmed last week.andM;The program, code-named Princeton, searches Dow Jones databases according topredetermined criteria set by the user and delivers that data to the PC viamodem, explained officials at Lotus Information Network Corp. (LINC), Lotus'wholly owned subsidiary in San Mateo, Calif., that develops real-timestock-information products.andM;The software, designed to be a stand-alone program, will be bundled with arun-time version of Desqview, Quarterdeck Office Systems Inc.'s multitaskingoperating environment.andM;The program was demonstrated by LINC officials at last week's Quarterdeckdevelopers conference in Santa Monica, Calif., and is set to be shipped tobeta-test  sites.andM;Broad Audience SoughtandM;LINC is looking for a broad audience for the software, according to officialsat the company.andP;  &quot;The program is being targeted toward middle and uppermanagers or anyone who uses a PC on a day-to-day basis and needs real-timenews,&quot; said LINC spokeswoman Julie Craig.andM;Users establish search criteria in an &quot;interest list,&quot; which the program thenuses to cull information from the Dow Jones News and Enhanced Current Quotedatabases, both offered by Dow Jones Information Services in Princeton, N.J.,andO;LINC officials said.andM;Via modem, Princeton accesses the databases and sends to any IBM PCheadlines, stories or stock quotes.andP;  Users can customize Princeton toretrieve information at weekly, hourly or daily intervals, or stock quotes ona 15-minute-delay basis.andP;  The program can also search for stories and datathat Dow Jones reported as much as 90 days beforehand.andM;The program offers three ways to view stories: a symbol view that providesnews related to a specific stock or industry category; an interest viewshowing all stories related to an interest list; and a full view listing allDow Jones stories chronologically.andM;LINC officials declined to comment on when the final version of the programwill be released.andO;</TEXT></DOC>